  "prompt": "What is the difference between level and edge triggered flip flops?",
  "response": "Here's a detailed comparison between level-triggered and edge-triggered flip-flops:\n\nLevel-Triggered Flip-Flops:\n1. State changes occur during entire active logic level\n2. Sensitive to signal's logic level (HIGH or LOW)\n3. Can have multiple state changes during active level\n4. Less stable and prone to potential race conditions\n5. Examples: Transparent latch\n6. More susceptible to timing-related errors\n7. Generally simpler circuit design\n\nEdge-Triggered Flip-Flops:\n1. State changes occur only at signal's rising or falling edge\n2. Sensitive to signal's transition (rising/falling edge)\n3. State changes happen at single, specific moment\n4. More stable and predictable behavior\n5. Examples: D flip-flop, JK flip-flop\n6. Better noise immunity\n7. More complex circuit design\n8. Preferred in modern digital systems\n9. Synchronous with clock signal\n\nKey Differences:\n- Triggering mechanism\n- Signal sensitivity\n- State change behavior\n- Timing characteristics\n- Circuit complexity\n- Reliability\n- Application suitability\n\nEdge-triggered flip-flops are generally preferred in modern digital design due to their more predictable and reliable performance.",
